202 (b) Provides skill development in phonemic awareness, phonics, fluency, vocabulary,
203 and comprehension;
204 (c) Includes a scientifically based and reliable assessment;
205 (d) Does not include the three-cueing system, as defined in section 170.014, to
206 decoding;
207 (e) Provides initial and ongoing analysis of each student's reading progress; and
208 [(e)] (f) Provides a curriculum in core academic subjects to assist the student in
209 maintaining or meeting proficiency levels for the appropriate grade in all academic subjects.
210 15. Each school district shall establish at each school, where applicable, an
211 intensive acceleration class for any student retained in grade three under subsection 9 of
212 this section who was previously retained in kindergarten, grade one, or grade two. The
213 intensive acceleration class shall include criteria established in subsections 13 and 14 of
214 this section and:
215 (1) Have a reduced teacher-student ratio; and

HCS HB 2872 11
216 (2) Provide explicit, systematic, sequential, and cumulative reading instruction
217 and intervention for the majority of student contact time each day.
218 [7.] 16. School districts and charter schools shall report to the department the specific
219 intensive reading interventions and supports implemented by the school district or charter
220 school pursuant to this section as well as the reading assessment data collected for grades
221 [kindergarten] one through [five] three. The department shall annually prescribe the
222 components of required or requested reports.
223 [8.] 17. (1) Each school district and charter school shall address reading proficiency
224 as part of its comprehensive school improvement plan, drawing upon information about
225 children from assessments conducted pursuant to subsection 1 of this section and the
226 prevalence of deficiencies identified by classroom, elementary school, and other student
227 characteristics. As part of its comprehensive school improvement plan or contract, each
228 school district or charter school shall review chronic early elementary absenteeism for its
229 impact on literacy development. If more than fifteen percent of an attendance center's
230 students are not at grade level in reading by the end of third grade, the comprehensive school
231 improvement plan or contract shall include strategies to reduce that percentage, including
232 school and community strategies to raise the percentage of students who are proficient in
233 reading.
234 (2) Each school district and charter school shall provide professional development
235 services to enhance the skills of elementary teachers in responding to children's unique
236 reading issues and needs and to increase the use of evidence-based strategies.
237 18. Each district school board shall, by October first of each year, report in
238 writing to the department of elementary and secondary education the following
239 information regarding the immediately preceding school year:
240 (1) The school board's policies and procedures regarding student retention and
241 promotion;
242 (2) By grade level, the number and percentage of all students in grades
243 kindergarten through three with reading deficiencies or substantial reading deficiencies;
244 (3) By grade level, the number and percentage of all students retained in grades
245 kindergarten to three due to substantial reading deficiencies; and
246 (4) The total number and percentage of students in grade three who were
247 promoted with good cause exemptions, delineated by each category of good cause
248 exemption specified in subsection 10 of this section.
249 19. Each public school shall make available to the public the title and author of
250 all reading curriculum materials adopted for each grade and the recommended reading
